{
    "blocks": [
        {
            "id": "intro_classes",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Creating Classes",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 1
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Imagine you're building a game with many characters. Each character has a name, health, and level. Instead of managing separate variables for each character, you can use a **class** to organize this data together."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "A **class** is like a blueprint or template. It defines what data and actions belong together."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "real_world_analogy",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Think of a **class** like a form you fill out at a doctor's office. The form has blank spaces for name, age, and address - that's the template."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "When different people fill out the form, each completed form is an **object**. Same template (class), but each object has different values (your name vs someone else's name)."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "what_are_objects",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**Objects** are the actual instances you create from a class. If `Car` is a class, then `Toyota`, `Ford`, and `Chevrolet` are objects - each is a specific car with its own brand, model, and characteristics."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "One class can create unlimited objects. Each object is independent and stores its own data."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "why_classes",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**Why use classes?** They group related data together, making your code organized and easier to manage. Instead of separate variables, everything about a car (brand, model, color) stays together."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quick_check_concept",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "If `Car` is a class, what are `Toyota`, `Ford`, and `Chevrolet`?"
                },
                {
                    "type": "mcq",
                    "content": "",
                    "properties": {
                        "question": "",
                        "options": [
                            "Objects created from the Car class",
                            "Other classes",
                            "Attributes of Car"
                        ],
                        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
                        "correctFeedback": "Correct! They are objects (instances) of the Car class.",
                        "incorrectFeedback": "They are objects - specific cars created from the Car class.",
                        "explanation": "A class is the template, objects are the actual instances with their own data."
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "basic_syntax",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Class Syntax",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "To create a class, use the `class` keyword followed by the class name and a colon."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "class Dog:\n    pass",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "This creates an empty `Dog` class. `pass` means \"do nothing for now\" - it's a placeholder."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "naming_convention",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**Naming convention**"
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Class names use CapitalCase, variables use snake_case."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "class BankAccount:\n    pass\n\nclass GameCharacter:\n    pass",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Good class names are descriptive nouns that represent what you're modeling."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quick_check_syntax",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "code_fill",
                    "content": "Create an empty class called `Car`.",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "lines": [
                            {
                                "code": "{1} {2}:",
                                "indent": 0,
                                "blank": "1,2"
