                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "adding_attributes",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Adding Attributes",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**Attributes** are variables that belong to a class. They store data about each object."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You can add attributes directly in the class or after creating an object. Let's see both ways:"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "class_attributes",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**Class attributes** are shared by all objects of that class. They represent data that's the same for every object of that class."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "To create a class attribute, define it inside the class. It will be shared by all objects of that class."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "class Dog:\n    species = \"Canine\"\n\nprint(Dog.species)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Canine"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "`species` is a class attribute. All dogs are canines, so this data is shared. You access it using the class name: `Dog.species`."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quick_check_class_attr",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "What are class attributes?"
                },
                {
                    "type": "mcq",
                    "content": "",
                    "properties": {
                        "question": "",
                        "options": [
                            "Functions inside a class",
                            "Data shared by all objects of the class"
                        ],
                        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
                        "correctFeedback": "Correct! Class attributes are shared by all instances.",
                        "incorrectFeedback": "Class attributes are shared data that all objects of that class have.",
                        "explanation": "Class attributes are like facts true for all members of the class."
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "instance_attributes",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**Instance attributes** also known as object attributes are unique to each object. Each object gets its own copy."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You can add attributes to an object after creating it using dot notation `object.attribute = value`."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "class Dog:\n    pass\n\n# Create object and add attributes\ndog1 = Dog()\ndog1.name = \"Buddy\"\ndog1.age = 3\n\nprint(dog1.name)\nprint(dog1.age)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Buddy\n3"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "We created a `Dog` object called `dog1`, then added `name` and `age` attributes specific to this dog."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "multiple_objects",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Each object can have different attribute values. For example, two dogs can have different names and ages."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "class Dog:\n    pass\n\ndog1 = Dog()\ndog1.name = \"Buddy\"\ndog1.age = 3\n\ndog2 = Dog()\ndog2.name = \"Max\"\ndog2.age = 5\n\nprint(f\"{dog1.name}: {dog1.age}\")\nprint(f\"{dog2.name}: {dog2.age}\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Buddy: 3\nMax: 5"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Both `dog1` and `dog2` are objects created from the `Dog` class. But each object stores its own unique data (`name` and `age`)."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quick_check_multiple",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "If you change `dog1.name`, what happens to `dog2.name`?"
                },
                {
                    "type": "mcq",
                    "content": "",
                    "properties": {
                        "question": "",
                        "options": [
                            "dog2.name also changes",
                            "Nothing - they're independent objects",
                            "An error occurs"
                        ],
                        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
                        "correctFeedback": "Correct! Each object has its own independent attributes.",
                        "incorrectFeedback": "Objects are independent - changing one doesn't affect others.",
                        "explanation": "Each object stores its own data separately from other objects."
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
