                        "hint": "Create object with Cat(), then add name attribute.",
                        "correctFeedback": "Perfect! You created an object and added an attribute.",
                        "incorrectFeedback": "Use Cat() to create an object, then object.name to add attribute.",
                        "explanation": "Objects are created from classes, then you can add attributes to them.",
                        "output": "Whiskers"
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "accessing_attributes",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You might have already noticed that you can access attributes using dot notation: `object.attribute`"
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "class Book:\n    pass\n\nbook = Book()\nbook.title = \"Python Basics\"\nbook.pages = 200\n\nprint(f\"Title: {book.title}\")\nprint(f\"Pages: {book.pages}\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Title: Python Basics\nPages: 200"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The dot `.` connects the object to its attributes. This is the same pattern you've used with lists and strings!"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "modifying_attributes",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You can also modify attributes just like regular variables."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "class Player:\n    pass\n\nplayer = Player()\n\nplayer.score = 0\nprint(f\"Score: {player.score}\")\n\nplayer.score = 100\nprint(f\"Score: {player.score}\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Score: 0\nScore: 100"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Attributes can be updated anytime. Each object keeps track of its own values independently."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quick_check_access",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "How do you access an object's attribute?"
                },
                {
                    "type": "mcq",
                    "content": "",
                    "properties": {
                        "question": "",
                        "options": [
                            "object.attribute",
                            "object[attribute]",
                            "object->attribute"
                        ],
                        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
                        "correctFeedback": "Correct! Use dot notation to access attributes.",
                        "incorrectFeedback": "Use object.attribute to access an attribute.",
                        "explanation": "Dot notation is the same pattern used for string and list methods."
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
